    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "Implementing implicit globbing for external utilities on Unix platforms is an attempt to _emulate_ the _typical_ native shell behavior there.\r\n\r\nDefining _typical_ is tricky, as it depends on whether it refers to the default shell for _interactive_ use - which is often `bash` - vs. running _scripts_ with the POSIX-features-only `/bin/sh` shell (which is `bash` in  its POSIX-compatible mode on some platforms (e.g., macOS), and `dash` on others (e.g, Ubuntu), and possibly a different implementation on others).\r\n\r\nEither way, the following - run on macOS 10.12.6 - shows that both `bash` and `dash` (which is the closest thing to a POSIX-features-only shell I'm aware of)  interpret unquoted `[]` as a _literal_ by default:\r\n\r\n```sh \r\n$ shall -c '/bin/echo []'\r\n✓ sh (bash variant)                       [0.01s]\r\n  []\r\n\r\n✓ dash                                    [0.00s]\r\n  []\r\n\r\n✓ bash                                    [0.00s]\r\n  []\r\n\r\n✗ zsh                                     [0.02s]\r\n  zsh:1: no matches found: []\r\n\r\n✓ ksh                                     [0.02s]\r\n  []\r\n\r\n```\r\n\r\n[`shall`](https://www.npmjs.com/package/shall) is a Unix utility of mine that runs a shell command against multiple POSIX-like shells.\r\n\r\n",
